Ismara's Doom — The Living World
Factions, Hold States, and Independent Activity

The Core Principle
Every strange thing happening in Skyrim when the party arrives somewhere is already happening. None of it was placed to confuse them. The confusion is a side effect of a world that has its own problems and doesn't know the party is the through-line connecting them.
The party is carrying Ismara through Skyrim. The Pale Fever follows their travel route. Local crises predate their arrival by weeks or months. When they look back from the end, it should feel like they spent ten sessions solving everyone else's problems while their own got catastrophically worse behind them.
The test for every local crisis: Would this be happening if the party never existed? If yes, it belongs. If no, cut it or rebuild it until it does.

The Cold Civil War
This is the background pressure that complicates everything without ever being the point.
King Torygg sits the throne in Solitude. He is young, earnest, and politically outmatched by Ulfric Stormcloak, who has been building his case against the White-Gold Concordat and the Empire's capitulation on Talos worship for years. The war has not broken out. Ulfric is not ready to move militarily yet — he is in the phase of organizing support, pressuring Jarls, testing loyalties, and waiting for a moment that will make his cause undeniable.
What this means on the ground:
Roads between holds are increasingly monitored. Imperial Legion checkpoints are present on major routes through Haafingar and Whiterun. Stormcloak sympathizers are active in Eastmarch, The Pale, and Winterhold. Some Jarls are being quietly pressured to declare before they're forced to. Torygg is working through his stewards and the court to hold the Moot together.
Intelligence networks on both sides are active. Unusual travelers get noticed. A group traveling with a heavily-wrapped silent figure who doesn't speak will generate questions — not necessarily hostile ones, but questions.
The Thalmor: The Aldmeri Dominion's embassy sits outside Solitude. Their agents are watching the civil war situation with satisfaction — a divided Empire weakens the only power that could threaten them. They are suppressing Talos worship aggressively. They are not tracking Ismara. They will never track Ismara. But they will notice the party in Solitude and may investigate them for entirely unrelated reasons, which reads as sinister and connected to the main plot and is not.
Torygg as a resource: The party could theoretically bring the truth to the High King. He has the political authority to mobilize a response to a Skyrim-wide catastrophe. Nobody in the world would think to suggest this — it would have to occur to the players themselves. If it does, they face the problem of explaining what's happening to someone with no framework for it, in a court where Ulfric has allies, while not revealing they've been the delivery mechanism for months. Handle this if it comes up. Don't plan for it.

Hold by Hold: What Is Already Happening

Eastmarch — Windhelm
Adventure 1 territory
The Situation:
Windhelm is Ulfric's city. He is its Jarl and the center of the Stormcloak political project. The city is divided — Nords in the city proper, Dunmer in the Gray Quarter, Argonians barred from the city entirely and working the docks in the cold. Ulfric ignores the ethnic tension because managing it costs political capital he is spending elsewhere.
What's Actually Happening:
Ulfric is in the middle of a careful intelligence operation. He has agents moving through every hold, gauging support and delivering private arguments to Jarls and thanes. He is also quietly accumulating grievances about Imperial overreach that he intends to present at a Moot. He is not thinking about the cold. He is not thinking about sick people. He is thinking about the throne.
The Gray Quarter is organizing. Brunwulf Free-Winter is the most visible advocate for Dunmer rights but there is a quieter network underneath him — Dunmer who have been in Windhelm for two generations and have stopped waiting for Nord goodwill to materialize. They move information between the Gray Quarter and the docks. They know things about Windhelm's underside that nobody in the Palace of Kings knows.
The docks are running a secondary economy that Ulfric's court officially doesn't see. Contraband, information, people moving without papers. The Argonian workers are part of this network. They are not criminals in any meaningful sense — they are people who have been excluded from legal structures and have built parallel ones.
How This Reads as Ismara-Adjacent:
The first node is a dockworker. The docks are already a place where people disappear without official notice. The Gray Quarter already has a heightened awareness of strange things happening to their people that the authorities aren't investigating. Suvaris Atheron is part of this community. Her behavior near the frozen dead reads as one more piece of something the Gray Quarter has been quietly watching for weeks.
When the Pale Fever appears, Windhelm's official response is to treat it as a disease from the Gray Quarter. This is wrong and reflects existing prejudice rather than evidence. The quarantine talk in Day 3 is aimed at the wrong neighborhood. The party walks into a city that is already misinterpreting its own crisis.
Ongoing After the Party Leaves:
Ulfric's intelligence operation continues. The Pale Fever continues and Windhelm's response worsens — the quarantine is eventually enforced against the Gray Quarter despite the disease showing no preference for Dunmer. Brunwulf's position becomes more difficult. The dock network starts moving information about the frozen people along its existing channels, which means by Adventure 3 there is a whisper network about the phenomenon that has no accurate information but has very good geographic coverage.

The Pale
Adventure 2 territory
The Situation:
The Pale is a hard, remote hold. Dawnstar is its capital — a mining and shipping town on the northern coast that is perpetually cold and perpetually underfunded. Jarl Skald the Elder is a Stormcloak sympathizer so committed to the cause that he has become politically useless, seeing Imperial agents in every shadow.
What's Actually Happening:
Dawnstar has a nightmare problem. The Skull of Corruption — an artifact of Vaermina, Daedric Prince of nightmares and psychological torment — is active in a cave outside the city. A priest of Vaermina named Erandur has been using it to periodically release nightmare spores into the town's population. Dawnstar's residents are sleep-deprived, irritable, and experiencing increasingly vivid collective nightmares. A priest of Mara named Erandur — who was once Vaermina's priest and is trying to undo what he did — has arrived in Dawnstar and is working quietly to destroy the artifact.
The nightmares are specific: they involve a vast cold presence, a sense of being frozen in place, and the feeling of being observed. Vaermina's spores are amplifying whatever psychological material exists in the dreamer. The cold presence in the nightmares is not Ismara. It is the dreamers' own anxiety about the spreading cold made monstrous by Vaermina's influence.
The road through the Pale has frozen people standing in the fields now. Farms are being abandoned. Skald's response is to blame Imperial sabotage.
How This Reads as Ismara-Adjacent:
Dawnstar's population is having nightmares about being frozen in place, watched by something vast and cold. People on the Pale road are frozen in place, watched by nothing. The content of the nightmares describes the actual phenomenon better than any investigation the party has conducted so far. This is coincidence. Vaermina is not tracking Ismara. Vaermina is amplifying what's already in people's heads.
The party will almost certainly investigate the nightmares as a potential Ismara thread. The investigation leads to a Daedric artifact in a cave and a priest with a complicated history. Completely unrelated. Completely real. Satisfying to resolve. The frozen people on the road remain when they leave.
Bersi's Farm:
Erik is frozen in the farmyard when the party passes through. Bersi asks them quietly if they know what's happening. He trusts them. He has heard about the Frostmere heroes from the same rumor network that Hrolf tapped. He believes they fixed this.
This is the moment the campaign's moral weight becomes personal. Don't rush it.
Ongoing After the Party Leaves:
Erandur eventually destroys the Skull of Corruption with or without the party's help — he has been working toward this for months and doesn't need them. The nightmares in Dawnstar stop. The frozen people on the road remain. Dawnstar slowly realizes the two things were not connected. Skald continues to blame the Empire for both.

Hjaalmarch — Morthal
Adventure 2 territory
The Situation:
Morthal is a small hold in a cold marsh. Jarl Idgrod Ravencroft is its leader — a woman who has visions, who is regarded as eccentric by the court and quietly respected by her people. Her steward Aslfur is more practically-minded and handles most of what passes for administration.
What's Actually Happening:
A vampire coven led by Movarth Piquine has been operating near Morthal for months. They have established a thrall network in the town. Alva, a local woman, is a vampire who has been feeding Hroggar false affection while feeding on his family — she burned his house with his wife and daughter inside to eliminate complications and has been using his grief as cover for her continued presence. The coven's headquarters is in an old fort in the marsh.
People in Morthal have been hollowed out. Not all of them — but several townspeople have that particular vacancy that comes from regular blood loss and mild compulsion. They function. They do their work. They don't remember where they were on certain nights.
Idgrod knows something is wrong. Her visions don't give her specifics but they give her the texture of it — a wrongness that has been building for months. She has been watching her townspeople and cannot name what she's watching.
How This Reads as Ismara-Adjacent:
Vacant-eyed townspeople who don't remember certain nights. A Jarl who speaks in oblique terms about something ancient and patient moving through her hold. Missing people. A general atmosphere of wrongness that nobody can quite articulate. This describes both vampire predation and the early stages of Ismara's work in a hold.
When Idgrod says "whatever is building has been patient — and now it is moving," she is talking about the vampire coven, which she has been watching for months and cannot confront directly without evidence. The party will hear this as a description of Ismara. They are both right and wrong.
Ongoing After the Party Leaves:
The vampire coven can be resolved — by the party, or by Morthal's own slow process of investigation eventually producing enough evidence for a response. If the party resolves it, the townspeople gradually recover. Morthal's general wrongness lifts. The frozen people in the hold do not unfreeze.

Haafingar — Solitude
Adventure 2 territory
The Situation:
Solitude is the Imperial capital of Skyrim. Torygg rules here with his wife Elisif, who is politically inexperienced but earnest. General Tullius commands the Imperial Legion from Castle Dour. The city is wealthy, cosmopolitan, and under pressure from every direction — Ulfric to the east, the Thalmor at the embassy, the East Empire Company making trade demands, and a High King trying to hold a fracturing political structure together.
What's Actually Happening:
The Thalmor are running an active intelligence operation out of their embassy and have agents throughout the city. They are primarily focused on Talos worship suppression and monitoring the civil war situation. They have a secondary interest in any magical phenomena that might indicate Daedric involvement in Skyrim's politics — the Daedra are theologically complex for the Dominion and they track their activity carefully.
The East Empire Company is applying pressure on Torygg's court for trade concessions. Their representative in Solitude is negotiating in bad faith and reporting back to interests in Cyrodiil that want Skyrim's resources regardless of which side wins the civil war.
The Bards College is having an internal crisis. The Burning of King Olaf festival has been banned by Elisif, who lost her husband and finds the festival's mockery of a dead king offensive. The College's director Viarmo is trying to navigate this without openly opposing the Jarl's grief. This is completely petty and political and has nothing to do with anything else.
How This Reads as Ismara-Adjacent:
The Thalmor notice the party. They are traveling with someone unusual. Thalmor agents will make discreet inquiries — not about Ismara, but about the party's identities, their employers, whether they are connected to the Stormcloak network. This attention feels sinister and connected. It is not. It is the Thalmor doing what the Thalmor always do.
If the party does anything visibly magical in Solitude, the Thalmor's interest increases. They have a protocol for flagging unusual magical activity to their arcane specialists. Those specialists will not identify Ismara's work — they have no framework for it — but they will produce a report that gets filed somewhere and may resurface in Adventure 5 as the College realizes the Thalmor have been tracking the same geographic anomalies from a different angle.
Ismara's Persuasion Moment:
At an inn in Solitude, she writes at length about Alduin. About what she watched burn while frozen. About permanence as the only solution she could find. This is her most direct argument. The city around them is doing what cities do — commerce, politics, small lives — and she is writing about the end of everything with complete calm.
Ongoing After the Party Leaves:
Torygg continues managing the political pressure. The Thalmor file their report. The Bards College eventually resolves the King Olaf situation one way or another. The city doesn't know the frozen people on the roads exist yet — the news hasn't reached Solitude's court in any form that Torygg's advisors have prioritized.

The Reach — Markarth
Adventure 3 territory
The Situation:
Markarth is a city built into Dwemer ruins that the Nords took from the Forsworn — the indigenous Reachmen — within living memory. Jarl Igmund holds the city for the Empire. The Silver-Blood family effectively controls the city's economy through their mine, their bank, and their grip on the local guard. Nepos the Old, a mild-mannered elderly man, coordinates Forsworn activity inside the city walls.
What's Actually Happening:
The Forsworn Conspiracy is active. Forsworn agents, coordinated by Nepos and answering ultimately to Madanach — the King in Rags, imprisoned in Cidhna Mine — are conducting targeted assassinations of city officials and Nord civilians. They are not random. Each target has been specifically chosen for their role in the original takeover or in the ongoing suppression of Reachmen rights.
The Silver-Blood family knows about the Conspiracy in the vague way that powerful people know about threats they have decided to monetize. They use the existence of Forsworn activity to justify keeping the mine running with prisoner labor, to justify their control of the guard, and to justify eliminating political rivals by having them accused of Forsworn sympathy.
The Hagravens — the Forsworn's magical leadership, women who have undergone a ritual transformation that trades their humanity for tremendous magical power — are conducting their own operation in the hills outside Markarth. They are binding people to the land using old Reach blood magic. Not killing them. Binding them. The bound people experience the Reach as something alive and hostile. Some wander back to the city changed. Some don't come back.
How This Reads as Ismara-Adjacent:
People found with marks on them that emerged from within the skin — Hagraven binding marks use a similar mechanism to Ismara's notation, emerging from within rather than being applied externally, because both draw on the same deep principle of substrate inscription. The marks look different up close but from a distance, to someone who has been looking at Pale Fever cases for two adventures, the resemblance is striking.
People bound to the Reach who wander back to the city are alive, present, but not entirely there. They describe a sense of being watched by something vast. This is the Reach's old magic, not Ismara. But the phenomenology overlaps.
The Forsworn are also creating geographic patterns — their ritual sites are positioned according to Reach cosmology in ways that, mapped against the node network, produce an overlapping but distinct geometry. A party that has been mapping Ismara's nodes and then starts mapping Hagraven ritual sites in the Reach will produce a confusing picture.
Ongoing After the Party Leaves:
The Conspiracy continues. The Silver-Bloods continue exploiting it. The Hagravens continue their binding work. Madanach sits in Cidhna Mine and waits. None of this resolves without intervention and none of it is connected to Ismara.

Whiterun Hold
Adventure 3 territory
The Situation:
Whiterun is the most central hold in Skyrim — all roads pass through it. Jarl Balgruuf the Greater is one of the most capable political operators in Skyrim, holding his neutrality through genuine skill rather than indifference. He sees the civil war coming and is buying time.
What's Actually Happening:
The Companions at Jorrvaskr have a secret: the inner circle are werewolves, transformed through a pact with Hircine. This is not actively causing visible harm to Whiterun, but it means the most respected warrior organization in the hold has a hidden cosmological entanglement that occasionally produces strange behavior, unexplained absences, and a particular evasiveness about certain topics. Kodlak Whitemane, the Harbinger, has spent years trying to find a way to cure the lycanthropy and die a clean death. He is old. He is running out of time.
The Battle-Born and Gray-Mane families are in an open feud that has become a proxy war for the civil war — Battle-Borns are Imperial, Gray-Manes are Stormcloak sympathizers. This makes Whiterun's social fabric tense in a specific, petty, very human way that Balgruuf is tired of managing.
A scholar, formerly of the College of Winterhold, has been independently investigating the frozen people phenomenon for six weeks. He correctly identified them as nodes in a deliberate ritual structure. He has a partial map. He has no idea who is responsible or why. He has been trying to get an audience with Balgruuf for two weeks and has been told the Jarl has more pressing concerns.
How This Reads as Ismara-Adjacent:
Kodlak will tell the party the cold spreading from the north is not natural. He has been Harbinger for decades and he has a sense for what Skyrim feels like. Something has changed. He doesn't know what. He would like to know what they're riding for.
This is the first time someone with genuine institutional authority and perceptive ability notices the party might know something. Kodlak is not suspicious of them. He is asking sincerely. What they tell him — or don't tell him — is a moral choice.
The scholar's partial map, if the party finds him, makes the ritual's scale visible for the first time. His geographic data is accurate. His interpretation is incomplete. He thinks it's a necromantic working of some kind.
Ongoing After the Party Leaves:
The scholar eventually gets his audience with Balgruuf. Balgruuf takes it seriously. He begins a quiet investigation that will produce nothing actionable before Adventure 5 because he has no framework for what he's investigating. Kodlak continues aging. The Companions continue managing their secret.

Falkreath Hold
Adventure 4 territory
The Situation:
Falkreath is a hold defined by death. Its capital has the largest graveyard in Skyrim — the hold has been a burial ground since the First Era and the soil is saturated with old interments. Jarl Siddgeir is young, corrupt, and primarily interested in maintaining the conditions of his own comfort. His steward Nenya runs the hold.
What's Actually Happening:
The Dark Brotherhood has a sanctuary in Falkreath Hold. They are operational. They are taking contracts. They are not connected to Ismara's work in any way, but their operational signature — apparently peaceful deaths, bodies found in positions that suggest no struggle, people who were alive at noon and dead by evening — overlaps visually with the aftermath of node placement in ways that will take careful examination to distinguish.
Hircine's presence is felt in Falkreath's forests. This is not active — Hircine is not conducting operations — but the hold has a history of lycanthropy that has left old magic in the landscape. Hunters sometimes feel watched. Animals behave strangely near certain groves. The forests of Falkreath are not safe in ways that have nothing to do with bandits.
The Dragon Cult has agents in Falkreath. This is the first hold where they are genuinely active. There is a deep ruin beneath the hold that predates the Dragon War — one of the original temples — and Cult agents have been moving in and out of it for months, retrieving records and preparing something. They don't know about Ismara yet. They are preparing for Alduin's return in their own timeline.
How This Reads as Ismara-Adjacent:
The first mandatory combat encounter of the campaign happens here — Dragon Cult agents. This is the first time the party faces an organized supernatural force that is also working against Ismara (though they don't know that yet). The Cult agents are not attacking because of Ismara. They are clearing the area around their ruin and the party has stumbled into their operational perimeter.
The Cult's records, if the party gains access to any of them, contain references to the sealing of Frostmere Barrow — the Dragon Cult did it, and their records of how contain the first documentary thread pointing toward the crown's vulnerability. They won't understand it yet. The information will sit in whatever notes they keep until Adventure 5 when the context arrives.
Ongoing After the Party Leaves:
The Dark Brotherhood continues operating. The Cult agents complete whatever they were retrieving and withdraw to another site. Siddgeir notices none of this.

The Rift — Riften
Adventure 4 territory
The Situation:
Riften is a corrupt city. Jarl Laila Law-Giver nominally rules, but Maven Black-Briar has the Thieves Guild, the Black-Briar meadery, and enough political connections to make Laila's rule largely ceremonial. The Guild operates out of the Ratway beneath the city. The skooma trade runs through the docks. Beggars disappear.
What's Actually Happening:
The Thieves Guild is in decline — not openly, but internally. Their run of bad luck has been too consistent to be natural and the senior members know it. Mercer Frey, the Guild Master, is covering up an ongoing betrayal that has been bleeding the Guild's operations for years. He has been eliminating anyone who gets close to the truth. The Guild is paranoid, fractured, and dangerous in the specific way of institutions that know something is wrong but cannot identify it.
Maven Black-Briar is consolidating. She has been positioning herself to be useful regardless of which side wins the civil war — she has quiet arrangements with both Imperial contacts and Stormcloak sympathizers. She is also expanding her skooma distribution network, which requires moving more product through the Rift and eliminating competitors. People who get in the way of this process disappear with troubling efficiency.
The skooma trade creates a population of people in Riften and the surrounding villages who are hollowed out in a very specific way — present but not there, going through motions, disconnected from their circumstances. This population overlaps with node victims in ways that will take careful examination to separate.
How This Reads as Ismara-Adjacent:
Riften has a visible population of people who are alive but not fully present. Some of them are skooma-addicted. Some of them are Guild-intimidated. Some of them are nodes. None of the locals can tell which are which. Neither can the party, initially.
Maven Black-Briar's intelligence network is good enough that she has noticed the party before they've been in the city a day. She doesn't know what they're doing but she knows they're not what they appear to be. She will make contact through an intermediary — not hostile, just establishing that she knows they exist and that Riften's affairs are her affairs.
Ismara's Revelation:
In Riften, Ismara tells them what she has been withholding. She writes what the ritual does to the nodes. All of it. She tells them because they deserve to know before the end.
The city around them is going about its corrupt, compromised, human business. She is sitting across from them and telling them she has been dissolving people into the earth.
Ongoing After the Party Leaves:
Mercer Frey's betrayal eventually surfaces with or without the party's involvement. Maven continues consolidating. The skooma trade continues. The nodes in the Rift remain standing in their positions.

Cross-Cutting Factions
These factions operate across multiple holds and need to be tracked as continuous presences rather than local phenomena.

The Dragon Cult
What they want: Alduin's return. The literal end of the world and time. They are true believers, not nihilists — they believe Alduin's consumption of the world is cosmologically necessary and that opposing it is a form of spiritual cowardice.
What they're doing: Preparing. Retrieving records from deep ruins. Reactivating old infrastructure. Placing agents in positions where they can move quickly when Alduin returns. They have been doing this for years and are in a late-preparation phase.
When they intersect with the party:
They don't know about Ismara until Adventure 3 or 4, when the ritual's scale becomes detectable through their own monitoring of Skyrim's cosmological state. When they figure out what she's doing, they correctly identify it as a direct threat to Alduin's return — you cannot eat a world that is also a mind fighting back.
They appear as combat in Adventure 4 (the mandatory encounter). They appear as a complex force in Adventure 5, wanting the same thing the party might want for entirely incompatible reasons.
The disgusting alignment: In Adventure 5, the Dragon Cult will offer the party information — specifically, their records of the Frostmere sealing ritual, which contain the key to the resonance disruption. They want the party to stop Ismara. They are willing to share what they know to make that happen. The party has to decide whether to take help from people who want to end the world, to get information they need to save it.
This should feel genuinely awful. There is no clean version of this choice.

The College of Winterhold
What they want: Knowledge. Specifically, Savos Aren wants to understand the Eye of Magnus, which he has been studying for years and which has been subtly influencing his priorities without his awareness.
What they're doing: Monitoring the Eye, attempting to understand the resonance anomalies they've been detecting, making things measurably worse with each intervention.
The critical error: Savos Aren has correctly identified the Eye of Magnus as a resonance point connected to the ritual. He believes he can use it to disrupt the ritual. He is catastrophically wrong. Deploying the Eye in the way he intends activates the transfer. He is a brilliant man working with incomplete information and an instrument that has been subtly warping his judgment for years.
The Urag gro-Shub thread: The College's restricted archive contains a single reference to Hjolmar Ice-Shaper — a lineage of Nordic artificers tagged "cognitive matrix theory." It is one line. It is not an answer. It is a thread that, pulled in the right direction, leads to Ismara's history. The party can find this in Adventure 3 if they access the archive.
The sealed chamber: There is a room in the College that Savos Aren will not discuss. It predates the current structure. What's in it is for the GM to determine based on the Orc player's engagement with the Namira thread — suggestions include an ancient body that will not decompose, a Namira shrine the College built over, or something that was once a person and is not anymore. Do not plan this room in detail until the Orc player gives you a reason to open it.

The Mortal Limit
By Adventure 4, the party hits a ceiling.
Ismara is a Master-tier sorceress who has spent 4,000 years calculating. Her body can be destroyed — she rebuilds it in hours. The ritual is 90% complete. Even if they could fight her, fighting her in the Eye of Magnus chamber while she is connected to the transfer is a different problem from anything they have encountered. She is not a boss to be defeated. She is a force with a plan that is almost finished.
Conventional means will not work. The party needs something else.
What exists in the world that could help:
The Dragon Cult's records — information about the resonance disruption, how the sealing worked, what the vulnerability is. Available at terrible moral cost.
The Eye of Magnus itself — if properly understood, the instrument that activates the transfer could theoretically also be turned on the transfer mid-process. Savos Aren cannot figure this out. The party might, with the right information from the right sources.
The Daedra — individual Daedric Princes have interests that may align with the party's needs at the moment they need them. Azura has an existing relationship with the College through her star. Meridia despises undead and might be approached regarding a Draugr Deathlord conducting a ritual on living people. Hircine has an existing thread through the Companions. None of these are guaranteed. All of them require the party to approach, to ask, to make an offer.
The Divines — Arkay has a specific interest in souls not being consumed as fuel. A sufficiently desperate party that has been paying attention to the theological implications of what Ismara is doing might make an argument to a Divine that this falls within their domain. This is harder, less reliable, and requires the party to have built something across the campaign — good standing, genuine faith, or a priest willing to carry their case.
The principle: None of these are solutions. They are each one piece of a solution the party has to build. The campaign does not end with a found weapon that fixes everything. It ends with the party using everything they know, everything they've built, and everything they're willing to do.

